[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering classpath scanning**\n\nI’m thinking about the classpath root scan and how it might uncover all class files, like the TemplateSpringTest class. I wonder how the JUnit engine identifies candidates for tests. It seems crucial for ensuring everything is detected correctly. I should remember how this impacts test discovery, especially in a testing framework. There’s definitely more to explore about how scans work and their effects on the JUnit process.\n\n**Exploring build paths**\n\nI’m considering whether I could use the in-memory known build path. The system property user.dir points to the root of the test project in both JVM and native environments. If it exists, I could use Paths.get(\"build/classes/java/test\").toAbsolutePath to retrieve that location. It seems like a reasonable approach to ensure I have the correct path, but I’ll need to double-check the existence of that directory first.\n\n**Evaluating test dependencies**\n\nI'm noticing that the test code doesn't compile directly against the launcher, except through something called TestAotProcessor. So, I need to ensure I have the right compile dependencies for @ClassTemplate and the provider. It looks like the current JUnit API could be lacking ClassTemplate, especially since Spring 7 is expecting JUnit 6 at runtime. I think I should infer from the build and test results to see if the existing tests are indeed using JUnit 6, as the build reports mention \"junit-jupiter.\"", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f01b53f83e9979b016a287c8338f88195b16b963027a56009\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKHzUkY2Vose0mIRU65Vgk5cBF8k6Qr6HHjSBYwjsBVEVbWuutGA9kPnaSHnFfUDtRlJ17tzltf6fg0oxBgQbUup-qAHKYQNBvFjV8zwBSQMgjtBzdIUfmZGDvymCAedOaCm3MXt8KrA9rHD6JMS0i48gdSBOz7Z269syAm7wKHMEAfWLEnJqu9nWzf-Q8hEULyT-bWy1t5PTIWRGwBo76biRuNz0mis1LKjnyM2az0SIgaQIJ2cJiolNd6D-mZPkx0TFsHuyK