ifies candidates for tests. It seems crucial for ensuring everything is detected correctly. I should remember how this impacts test discovery, especially in a testing framework. There’s definitely more to explore about how scans work and their effects on the JUnit process.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring build paths**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I could use the in-memory known build path. The system property user.dir points to the root of the test project in both JVM and native environments. If it exists, I could use Paths.get(\\\"build/classes/java/test\\\").toAbsolutePath to retrieve that location. It seems like a reasonable approach to ensure I have the correct path, but I’ll need to double-check the existence of that directory first.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test dependencies**\\n\\nI'm noticing that the test code doesn't compile directly against the launcher, except through something called TestAotProcessor. So, I need to ensure I have the right compile dependencies for @ClassTemplate and the provider. It looks like the current JUnit API could be lacking ClassTemplate, especially since Spring 7 is expecting JUnit 6 at runtime. I think I should infer from the build and test results to see if the existing tests are indeed using JUnit 6, as the build reports mention \\\"junit-jupiter.\\\"\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_PCMRuBvE4Tih7HZAzi2IYIk8|fc_0f01b53f83e9979b016a287cd4b3d48195bc5802c3910217e6", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"junit-jupiter-api|junit-jupiter-engine|6\\.0\" tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/build/reports/problems tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/build/test-results/test -n | head -40"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1059, "output": 2665, "cacheRead": 38912, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42636, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopRea